 to formal policy frameworks, it identifies lessons for future planning at the neighbourhood scale. It is not a manual on community planning practice, nor does it provide a formula for producing parish or neighbourhood plans. But in the context of the latest 'localism' agenda in England it, first, examines the potential contribution of neighbourhood planning to building a 'collaborative democracy' and, second, asks how much movement towards genuine local partnership, and consensus around development decisions, can be achieved through the rescaling of 'statutory' planning as opposed to expending greater effort locally on building stronger relationships, and generating trust, between 'people and planning'  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aNeighborhood planningvCase studieszEngland. 0aNeighborhood planningzEngland. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aRobinson, Steve, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z9783111196213oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978144730007640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447300083423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447300083/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPc1995d2013